# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hydraulic-fluid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] An **adaptive compliant wing** is a wing which is flexible enough for aspects of its shape to be changed in flight.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible wings have a number of benefits.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] Conventional flight control mechanisms operate using hinges, resulting in disruptions to the airflow, vortices, and in some cases, separation of the airflow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] These effects contribute to the drag of the aircraft, resulting in less efficiency and higher fuel costs.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible aerofoils can manipulate aerodynamic forces with less disruptions to the flow, resulting in less aerodynamic drag and improved fuel economy.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changing the shape of an aerodynamic surface has a direct effect on its aerodynamic properties.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] According to the flow condition and to the initial shape of the part, each shape variation (curvature, incidence, twist...) can have a different impact on the resulting forces and moments.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] This characteristic is actively pursued in adaptive wings which – by nature of their distributed compliance – can attain shape changes in a continuous, smooth, gap-free manner.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] By altering these geometrical parameters, the forces and moments can be modified, permitting to tailor them to the specific flight condition (e.g. for drag reduction) or to perform maneuvers (e.g. roll).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] Shape adaptation can be classified according to the motion it enables.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changes of the airfoil shapes include altering its twist, and changing its camber and thickness distribution.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] An adaptive compliant wing designed by FlexSys Inc. features a variable-camber trailing edge which can be deflected up to ±10°, thus acting like a flap-equipped wing, but without the individual segments and gaps typical in a flap system.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing itself can be twisted up to 1° per foot of span.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing's shape can be changed at a rate of 30° per second, which is ideal for gust load alleviation.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] The development of the adaptive compliant wing is being sponsored by the U.S.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] Initially, the wing was tested in a wind tunnel, and then a 50-inch (1.3 m) section of wing was flight tested on board the Scaled Composites White Knight research aircraft in a seven-flight, 20-hour program operated from the Mojave Spaceport.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] Adaptive compliant wings are also investigated at ETH Zurich in the frame of the Smart airfoil project.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] The EU-funded Flexop program aims to develop to enable higher wing aspect ratio for less induced drag with lighter, more flexible airliner wings, along developing active flutter suppression for flexible wings.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] Partners include Hungary's MTA SZTAKI, Airbus, Austria's FACC, Inasco of Greece, Delft University of Technology, German aerospace center DLR, TUM, the UK's University of Bristol and RWTH Aachen University in Germany.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] On 19 November 2019, a 7 m (23 ft) span jet-powered UAV demonstrator with an aeroelastically tailored wing for passive load alleviation was flown in Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany, previously flown with a carbon-fiber, rigid wing to establish baseline performance.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] It has a conventional tube-and-wing configuration, unlike the blended wing body of the Lockheed Martin X-56.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] It follows the Grumman X-29 demonstrator in 1984, with more refined fiber orientations.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] The flexible wing is 4% lighter than the rigid one.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] The 54-month, €6.67 million ($7.4 million) project ends in November 2019, followed by the €3.85 million FLiPASED program from September 2019 until December 2022, using all the movable surfaces.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] The glass fiber flutter wing should to be flown in 2020, with unstable aeroelastic modes under 55 m/s (107 kn) that must be actively suppressed.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] With optimized aeroelastic tailoring and active flutter suppression, an aspect ratio of 12.4 could reduce fuel-burn by 5%, and 7% are targeted.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adaptive-compliant-wing] FLiPASED is also led by MTA SZTAKI and include partners TUM, DLR and French aerospace research agency ONERA.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Adipic acid is produced by oxidation of a mixture of cyclohexanone and cyclohexanol, which is called **KA oil**, an abbreviation of ketone-alcohol oil.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Side products of the method include glutaric and succinic acids.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Nitrous oxide is produced in about one to one mole ratio to the adipic acid, as well, via the intermediacy of a nitrolic acid.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Related processes start from cyclohexanol, which is obtained from the hydrogenation of phenol.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Several methods have been developed by carbonylation of butadiene.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Another method is oxidative cleavage of cyclohexene using hydrogen peroxide.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Auguste Laurent discovered adipic acid in 1837 by oxidation of various fats with nitric acid via sebacic acid and gave it the current name because of that (ultimately from Latin *adeps*, *adipis* – 'animal fat'; cf. adipose tissue).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Adipic acid is a diprotic acid (it has two acidic groups).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] The pKa values for their successive deprotonations are 4.41 and 5.41.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] With the carboxylate groups separated by four methylene groups, adipic acid is suited for intramolecular condensation reactions.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Upon treatment with barium hydroxide at elevated temperatures, it undergoes ketonization to give cyclopentanone.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] About 60% of the 2.5 billion kg of adipic acid produced annually is used as monomer for the production of nylon by a polycondensation reaction with hexamethylene diamine forming nylon 66.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Other major applications also involve polymers; it is a monomer for production of polyurethane and its esters are plasticizers, especially in PVC.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Adipic acid has been incorporated into controlled-release formulation matrix tablets to obtain pH-independent release for both weakly basic and weakly acidic drugs.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] It has also been incorporated into the polymeric coating of hydrophilic monolithic systems to modulate the intragel pH, resulting in zero-order release of a hydrophilic drug.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] The disintegration at intestinal pH of the enteric polymer shellac has been reported to improve when adipic acid was used as a pore-forming agent without affecting release in the acidic media.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Other controlled-release formulations have included adipic acid with the intention of obtaining a late-burst release profile.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Small but significant amounts of adipic acid are used as a food ingredient as a flavorant and gelling aid.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] It is used in some calcium carbonate antacids to make them tart.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] As an acidulant in baking powders, it avoids the undesirable hygroscopic properties of tartaric acid.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Adipic acid, rare in nature, does occur naturally in beets, but this is not an economical source for commerce compared to industrial synthesis.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] Adipic acid, like most carboxylic acids, is a mild skin irritant.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] It is mildly toxic, with a median lethal dose of 3600 mg/kg for oral ingestion by rats.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] The production of adipic acid is linked to emissions of N 2O, a potent greenhouse gas and cause of stratospheric ozone depletion.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] The anionic (HO2C(CH2)4CO2−) and dianionic (−O2C(CH2)4CO2−) forms of adipic acid are referred to as **adipates**.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/adipic-acid] An adipate compound is a carboxylate salt or ester of the acid.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aerodynamics] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The **aft pressure bulkhead** or **rear pressure bulkhead** is the rear component of the pressure seal in all aircraft that cruise in a tropopause zone in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] It helps maintain pressure when stratocruising and protects the aircraft from bursting due to the higher internal pressure.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aft pressure bulkheads can either be curved, which reduces the amount of metal needed at the cost of reducing the usable space in the airliner, or flat, which gives more internal space but also more weight.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Patents have been filed that propose deliberately creating cavities within the rear bulkhead with the purpose of providing more usable cabin space.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] On several airliners, production of the rear pressure bulkhead has been outsourced to third party manufacturers.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] While typically being a time-consuming and somewhat uncommon process, an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead can be wholly replaced.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the twenty-first century, various parties became increasingly interested in developing aft pressure bulkheads composed from composite materials, seeking benefits such as lower manufacturing costs, easier sealing, elimination of corrosion risk, along with weight and part count reductions.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the early 2000s, Airbus Group developed the largest manufactured resin film infusion structure then in production to function as the aft pressure bulkhead for their double-decker A380 airliner.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Multiple instances of damage to the aft pressure bulkhead have occurred; while a few cases have led to serious failures leading to aircraft losses, others have proven to be survivable.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aviation certifying authorities have often mandated inspections of an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead in the interest of safety.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Various techniques have been devised to determine the integrity of the rear pressure bulkhead; these have been used not only to inspect in-service examples but also in the design process, helping to design efficient bulkheads that possess sufficient strength to ensure a safe operational life.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1971, British European Airways Flight 706 crashed in Belgium, killing all 63 on board; the cause was determined to be corrosion of the rear pressure bulkhead by fluid contamination, perhaps from the lavatory.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The corrosion was not detectable by the inspection techniques at the time.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1985, Japan Air Lines Flight 123 crashed after a catastrophic failure of the aft pressure bulkhead.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The failure occurred due to faulty repair of the bulkhead after a tailstrike seven years earlier, when a single repair patch plate was incorrectly cut in two "to make it fit".
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Failure of the bulkhead damaged hydraulic pipes passing through.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Boeing later calculated that the incorrect installation would be expected to fail after approximately 10,000 pressurizations; the repaired aircraft accomplished 12,318 successful flights before the crash.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During 2013, National Airlines Flight 102 crashed after loose freight on the main deck is believed to have penetrated the aft pressure bulkhead and caused damage to control systems in the vicinity of the bulkhead.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/astm] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] A **hydraulic fluid** or **hydraulic liquid** is the medium by which power is transferred in hydraulic machinery.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Common hydraulic fluids are based on mineral oil or water.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Examples of equipment that might use hydraulic fluids are excavators and backhoes, hydraulic brakes, power steering systems, automatic transmissions, garbage trucks, aircraft flight control systems, lifts, and industrial machinery.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Hydraulic systems like the ones mentioned above will work most efficiently if the hydraulic fluid used has zero compressibility.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] The primary function of a hydraulic fluid is to convey power.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] In use, however, there are other important functions of hydraulic fluid such as protection of the hydraulic machine components.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Although many liquids can be used, such as water, almost all hydraulic fluids are less corrosive and more viscous.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] The petrochemical mineral oil is the predominant component, the particular type being dictated by viscosity.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Poly alpha olefins, which are petroleum-derived synthetic lubricating oils, are mixed with the mineral oil.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Other base stocks are used for specialty applications, such as for fire resistance and extreme temperature applications.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Some examples include: glycol ethers, organophosphate ester, polyalphaolefin, propylene glycol, and silicone oils.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Hydraulic fluids can contain a wide range of additives as corrosion inhibitors (incl acid scavengers), anti-erosion additives, etc.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] NaK-77, a eutectic alloy of sodium and potassium, can be used as a hydraulic fluid in high-temperature and high-radiation environments, for temperature ranges of 10 to 1,400 °F (−12 to 760 °C).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Its bulk modulus at 1,000 °F (538 °C) is 310,000 psi (2.14 GPa), higher than of a hydraulic oil at room temperature.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Its lubricity is poor, so positive-displacement pumps are unsuitable and centrifugal pumps have to be used.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] The addition of caesium shifts the useful temperature range to −95 to 1,300 °F (−71 to 704 °C).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] The NaK-77 alloy was tested in hydraulic and fluidic systems for the Supersonic Low Altitude Missile.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Environmentally sensitive applications (e.g. farm tractors and marine dredging) may benefit from using biodegradable hydraulic fluids.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Natural oils such as rapeseed are used as base stocks for fluids where biodegradability and renewable sources are considered important, e.g. when there is the risk of an oil spill.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Typically these oils are available as ISO 32, ISO 46, and ISO 68 specification oils.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] ASTM standards ASTM-D-6006, Guide for Assessing Biodegradability of Hydraulic Fluids and ASTM-D-6046, Standard Classification of Hydraulic Fluids for Environmental Impact are relevant.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Because industrial hydraulic systems operate at hundreds to thousands of PSI and temperatures reaching hundreds of degrees Celsius, severe injuries and death can result from component failures and care must always be taken when performing maintenance on hydraulic systems.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Fire resistance is a property available with specialized fluids.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Water-glycol and polyol-ester are some of these specialized fluids that contain excellent thermal and hydrolytic properties, which aid in fire resistance.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Brake fluid is a subtype of hydraulic fluid with high boiling point, both when new (specified by the equilibrium boiling point) and after absorption of water vapor (specified by wet boiling point).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Under the heat of braking, both free water and water vapor in a braking system can boil into a compressible vapor, resulting in brake failure.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Glycol-ether based fluids are hygroscopic, and absorbed moisture will greatly reduce the boiling point over time.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Mineral oil and silicone based fluids are not hygroscopic.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Power steering fluid is a sub type of hydraulic fluid.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Most are mineral oil or silicone based fluids, while some use automatic transmission fluid, made from synthetic base oil.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Automatic transmissions use fluids for their lubrication, cooling and hydraulic properties for viscous couplings.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Use of the wrong type of fluid can lead to failure of the power steering pump.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] As aircraft performance increased in the mid-20th century, the amount of force required to operate mechanical flight controls became excessive, and hydraulic systems were introduced to reduce pilot effort.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] The hydraulic actuators are controlled by valves; these in turn are operated directly by input from the aircrew (hydro-mechanical) or by computers obeying control laws (fly by wire).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Hydraulic power is used for other purposes.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] It can be stored in accumulators to start an auxiliary power unit (APU) for self-starting the aircraft's main engines.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Many aircraft equipped with the M61 family of cannon use hydraulic power to drive the gun system, permitting reliable high rates of fire.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] The hydraulic power itself comes from pumps driven by the engines directly, or by electrically driven pumps.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] In modern commercial aircraft these are electrically driven pumps; should all the engines fail in flight the pilot will deploy a propeller-driven electric generator called a *Ram-Air Turbine* (RAT) which is concealed under the fuselage.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] This provides electrical power for the hydraulic pumps and control systems as power is no longer available from the engines.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] In that system and others, electric pumps can provide both redundancy and the means of operating hydraulic systems without the engines operating, which can be very useful during maintenance.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Special, stringent care is required when handling aircraft hydraulic fluid, as it is critical to flight safety that it stay free from contamination.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] It is also necessary to strictly adhere to authorized references when servicing or repairing any aircraft system.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Samples from aircraft hydraulic systems are taken during heavy aircraft maintenance checks (primarily C and D checks) to check contamination.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Military Spec 1246C is one fluid contamination specification.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] The ISO fluid contamination scale assigns a contamination category based on particle size count and distribution.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] The properties of HLP 32 hydraulic oil make it ideal for lubricating machine tools.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Synthetic hydrocarbon base: These synthetic fluids are compatible with mineral-base hydraulic fluids and were developed to address the low flash point draw back of mineral based hydraulic fluids.
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Commonly used hydraulic oil viscosities fall under the ISO VG (Viscosity Grade) classification system, which is based on the oil's kinematic viscosity at 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:hydraulic-fluid/hydraulic-fluid] Additional viscosities such as the following, are also used, but less frequently or for specific low/high-temperature applications.
